y & Wortley by-election]]\n|18 September 2008\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n{{Party name with colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n|-bgcolor=lightblue\n|[[2008 Leeds City Council election#By-elections between 2008 and 2010|Temple Newsam by-election]]\n|2 April 2009\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n|-bgcolor=pink\n|[[2008 Leeds City Council election#By-elections between 2008 and 2010|Hyde Park & Woodhouse by-election]]\n|18 February 2010\n{{Party name with colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n|-\n|[[2010 Leeds City Council election#By-elections between 2010 and 2011|Guiseley & Rawdon by-election]]\n|14 October 2010\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n|-\n|[[2012 Leeds City Council election#By-elections between 2012 and 2014|Cross Gates & Whinmoor by-election]]\n|2 May 2013\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n{{Party name with colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n|-\n|[[2019 Leeds City Council election#By-elections between 2019 and 2020|Wetherby by-election]]\n|12 December 2019\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n{{Party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.leeds.gov.uk Leeds City Council]\n\n{{West Yorkshire elections}}\n{{Metropolitan districts of England}}\n\n[[Category:Leeds City Council elections| ]]\n[[Category:Council elections in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Local government in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Elections in Leeds]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan borough council elections in England|Leeds]]\n", "name_user": "LeedsOwlNew", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBorough result maps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leeds_City_Council_elections"}
{"title_page": "Chris Trotter", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=October 2014}}\n[[File:Trotter, Chris (Alliance).jpg|right|thumb|Chris Trotter speaking at the [[Alliance (New Zealand political party)|Alliance]] party conference in 2007]]\n'''Chris Trotter''' (born c. 1956) is a [[left-wing|left]]-leaning political commentator in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10608914&pnum=0|title=TVNZ looking at options for Paul Henry|last=Drinnan|first=John|date=13 November 2009|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> He is the editor of the occasional ''[[Political Review]]'' magazine, and is a regular speaker, orator and singer at [[left-wing]], [[labor union|union]] and [[socialist]] events.\n\n==Biography==\nChris Trotter has worked for unions and was on the New Zealand council of the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/politics/news/article.cfm?c_id=280&objectid=10461671&pnum=0|title=Left, right, left - the march of NZ history since the '70s|last=McCammon|first=Belinda |date=5 September 2007|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> He writes the \"From the Left\" column in the ''[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|Dominion Post]]'', and has also contributed to the ''[[Independent Financial Review]]''. He makes semi-frequent television appearances as a political commentator.\n\nHe has attracted criticism from other broad left critics who regard his knowledge of [[feminist]], indigenous and [[LGBT]] politics to be insignificant, particularly insofar as their own distributive justice dimensions are concerned <ref>http://www.norightturn.blogspot.com</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gaynz.com/blog/redqueen |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829054049/http://gaynz.com/blog/redqueen/ |archive-date=29 August 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTrotter is the author of ''No Left Turn'', a political history of New Zealand.<ref name=\"nlt\">{{cite book | title=No Left Turn: The Distortion of New Zealand's History by Greed, Bigotry, and Right-Wing Politics| last=Trotter| first=Chris| year=2007| publisher=Random House| location=New Zealand| isbn=978-1869418090}}</ref> Novelist, poet and critic [[C K Stead]] described the book as \"a dashingly written and persuasive elegy for the Scandinavian-style socialist democracy New Zealand might have been, and at the same time a realistic (though at times appropriately angry) acknowledgement that, given the forces, internal and external, ranged against it, the chances of it happening, and lasting, were never very good.\"<ref name=\"ckstead\">{{cite journal | title=Our Favourite Things| journal=Dominion Post| date=8 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, he had sex with his mum.....said that [[Helen Clark]] should stand down before the [[2008 New Zealand general election|election]] and be replaced by [[Phil Goff]], who he thought may have been Labour's only hope of regaining ground with struggling families. He has since recanted, arguing that Goff should have stood down in his turn before the [[2011 New Zealand general election]], arguing that [[David Cunliffe]] should replace him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/282462|title=Labour poll-axed |date=23 February 2008|work=The Dominion Post |accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref>http://www.bowalleyroad.com/2010/08/leader-labour-needs-to-have.html{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Trotter joined the Free Speech Coalition, a group of former politicians, lawyers, journalists, and academics that pursued legal action against the [[Mayor of Auckland]] [[Phil Goff]] for denying [[Auckland Council]] facilities to two Canadian [[alt-right]] activists [[Lauren Southern]] and [[Stefan Molyneux]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Free Speech Coalition website |url=https://freespeechcoalition.nz/ |publisher=Free Speech Coalition |accessdate=5 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805112726/https://freespeechcoalition.nz/ |archive-date=5 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Free Speech Coalition on details of legal action |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1807/S00202/free-speech-coalition-on-details-of-legal-action.htm |accessdate=5 August 2018 |work=Free Speech Coalition |publisher=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Truebridge |first1=Nick |title=Free speech group raises $50k to challenge Auckland Council over far-Right speaker ban |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/105377682/free-speech-group-raises-50k-to-challenge-auckland-council-over-farright-speaker-ban |accessdate=5 August 2018 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=10 July 2018}}</ref> Trotter justified his defense of the two alt-right activists' free speech by arguing that left-wing opponents of the tour lacked the courage to debate the alt-right.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trotter |first1=Chris |title=Do We Really Lack the Courage to Debate the Alt-Right? Do We Really Lack the Ideas to Defeat Them? |url=http://bowalleyroad.blogspot.com/2018/07/do-we-really-lack-courage-to-debate-alt.html |website=Bowalley Road |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bowalleyroad.blogspot.com Chris Trotter's blog]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trotter, Chris}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand columnists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand left-wing activists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Labour Party politicians]]\n[[Category:NewLabour Party (New Zealand) politicians]]\n[[Category:Bruce Jesson Memorial lecturers]]\n\n\n{{poli-bio-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-politician-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=October 2014}}\n[[File:Trotter, Chris (Alliance).jpg|right|thumb|Chris Trotter speaking at the [[Alliance (New Zealand political party)|Alliance]] party conference in 2007]]\n'''Chris Trotter''' (born c. 1956) is a [[left-wing|left]]-leaning political commentator in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10608914&pnum=0|title=TVNZ looking at options for Paul Henry|last=Drinnan|first=John|date=13 November 2009|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> He is the editor of the occasional ''[[Political Review]]'' magazine, and is a regular speaker, orator and singer at [[left-wing]], [[labor union|union]] and [[socialist]] events.\n\n==Biography==\nChris Trotter has worked for unions and was on the New Zealand council of the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/politics/news/article.cfm?c_id=280&objectid=10461671&pnum=0|title=Left, right, left - the march of NZ history since the '70s|last=McCammon|first=Belinda |date=5 September 2007|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> He writes the \"From the Left\" column in the ''[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|Dominion Post]]'', and has also contributed to the ''[[Independent Financial Review]]''. He makes semi-frequent television appearances as a political commentator.\n\nHe has attracted criticism from other broad left critics who regard his knowledge of [[feminist]], indigenous and [[LGBT]] politics to be insignificant, particularly insofar as their own distributive justice dimensions are concerned <ref>http://www.norightturn.blogspot.com</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gaynz.com/blog/redqueen |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829054049/http://gaynz.com/blog/redqueen/ |archive-date=29 August 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTrotter is the author of ''No Left Turn'', a political history of New Zealand.<ref name=\"nlt\">{{cite book | title=No Left Turn: The Distortion of New Zealand's History by Greed, Bigotry, and Right-Wing Politics| last=Trotter| first=Chris| year=2007| publisher=Random House| location=New Zealand| isbn=978-1869418090}}</ref> Novelist, poet and critic [[C K Stead]] described the book as \"a dashingly written and persuasive elegy for the Scandinavian-style socialist democracy New Zealand might have been, and at the same time a realistic (though at times appropriately angry) acknowledgement that, given the forces, internal and external, ranged against it, the chances of it happening, and lasting, were never very good.\"<ref name=\"ckstead\">{{cite journal | title=Our Favourite Things| journal=Dominion Post| date=8 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, he said that [[Helen Clark]] should stand down before the [[2008 New Zealand general election|election]] and be replaced by [[Phil Goff]], who he thought may have been Labour's only hope of regaining ground with struggling families. He has since recanted, arguing that Goff should have stood down in his turn before the [[2011 New Zealand general election]], arguing that [[David Cunliffe]] should replace him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/282462|title=Labour poll-axed |date=23 February 2008|work=The Dominion Post |accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref><ref>http://www.bowalleyroad.com/2010/08/leader-labour-needs-to-have.html{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Trotter joined the Free Speech Coalition, a group of former politicians, lawyers, journalists, and academics that pursued legal action against the [[Mayor of Auckland]] [[Phil Goff]] for denying [[Auckland Council]] facilities to two Canadian [[alt-right]] activists [[Lauren Southern]] and [[Stefan Molyneux]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Free Speech Coalition website |url=https://freespeechcoalition.nz/ |publisher=Free Speech Coalition |accessdate=5 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805112726/https://freespeechcoalition.nz/ |archive-date=5 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Free Speech Coalition on details of legal action |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1807/S00202/free-speech-coalition-on-details-of-legal-action.htm |accessdate=5 August 2018 |work=Free Speech Coalition |publisher=[[Scoop (website)|Scoop]] |date=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Truebridge |first1=Nick |title=Free speech group raises $50k to challenge Auckland Council over far-Right speaker ban |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/105377682/free-speech-group-raises-50k-to-challenge-auckland-council-over-farright-speaker-ban |accessdate=5 August 2018 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=10 July 2018}}</ref> Trotter justified his defense of the two alt-right activists' free speech by arguing that left-wing opponents of the tour lacked the courage to debate the alt-right.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trotter |first1=Chris |title=Do We Really Lack the Courage to Debate the Alt-Right? Do We Really Lack the Ideas to Defeat Them? |url=http://bowalleyroad.blogspot.com/2018/07/do-we-really-lack-courage-to-debate-alt.html |website=Bowalley Road |accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bowalleyroad.blogspot.com Chris Trotter's blog]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trotter, Chris}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand columnists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand left-wing activists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Labour Party politicians]]\n[[Category:NewLabour Party (New Zealand) politicians]]\n[[Category:Bruce Jesson Memorial lecturers]]\n\n\n{{poli-bio-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-politician-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "131.242.7.11", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBiography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Trotter"}
{"title_page": "Aidan Gallagher", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Aidan Gallagher\n| image         = Aidan Gallagher - 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| caption       = Gallagher in 2018\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|2003|9|18}}\n| birth_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Actor, Singer\n| years_active  = 2013\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Aidan Gallagher''' (born September 18, 2003<ref>See: {{bulleted list \n|{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BKfRVYNBgfy/ |title=I'm official. ThirTEEN! |author=Gallagher, Aidan |publisher=aidanrgallagher |via=Instagram |date=September 18, 2016}}\n|{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BZKes23njEk/ |title=Thank you |author=Gallagher, Aidan |publisher=aidanrgallagher |via=Instagram |date=September 18, 2017 }} \n|{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bn3dRhDnBUX/ |title=15 \ud83c\udf82 |author=Gallagher, Aidan |publisher=aidanrgallagher |via=Instagram |date=September 18, 2018}} \n}}</ref>) is an American actor. His first major role was portraying one of the quadruplets, Nicky Harper, in the [[Nickelodeon]] television series ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/nickelodeon-greenlights-new-comedy-from-dan-schneider-two-other-live-action-series-698354/|title=Nickelodeon Greenlights New Comedy from Dan Schneider, Two Other Live-Action Series|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 13, 2014|access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, Gallagher began portraying Number Five in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/02/15/umbrella-academy-aidan-gallagher-number-five/ |title=Umbrella Academy actor explains how he nailed the timey-wimey weirdness of Number Five |first=Christian|last= Holub|date=February 15, 2019 |work=Entertainment Weekly }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGallagher first appeared in a minor role in a 2013 episode of ''[[Modern Family]]''. He was in the short film ''You & Me'' and was in the [[CBS]] television pilot ''Jacked Up'', which was not picked up and never aired.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/who-plays-number-5-in-the-umbrella-academy.html/|title=Who Plays Number 5 in 'The Umbrella Academy?'|last=Lezmi|first=Josh|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-02-28|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=March 04|first3=2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm6200897/bio|title=Aidan Gallagher - IMDb Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He then landed a major role in Nickelodeon's ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]'' as Nicky Harper,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/reviews/tv-review-nickelodeons-nicky-ricky-dicky-and-dawn-1201298288/ |title=TV Review: Nickelodeon's 'Nicky, Ricky, Dicky and Dawn' |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=September 12, 2014 }}</ref> for which he was nominated [[Kids' Choice Award for Favorite Male TV Star|Favorite Male TV Star]] in the [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]] in 2016 and 2017.<ref name=kids2016>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2016-kids-choice-award-nominees-867404/item/favorite-tv-show-2016-kids-867415 |title=Kids' Choice Awards: Adele, Justin Bieber, 'Star Wars' Among Nominees |date=  February 18, 2016|work=Hollywood Reporter }}</ref><ref name=kids2017>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/kids-choice-awards-complete-list-nominees-970757/item/2017-kids-choice-awards-favorite-tv-show-kids-show-970759 |title=Kids' Choice Awards: Justin Timberlake, Kevin Hart Top Nominations |date=February 2, 2017 |first= Lexy |last=Perez|work=Hollywood Reporter }}</ref> He was in the show for four seasons until it ended in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/school-of-rock-nicky-ricky-dicky-and-dawn-canceled-nickelodeon-1202616047/ |title='School of Rock,' 'Nicky, Ricky, Dicky and Dawn' Canceled at Nickelodeon |first= Joe |last= Otterson |work=Variety |date=November 15, 2018 }}</ref>  \n\nIn 2017, Gallagher was cast in the role of Number Five in ''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]'', which was released in February 2019 on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/umbrella-academy-series-netflix-cast-1202627134/|title='Umbrella Academy' Netflix Series Rounds Out Cast With 'Game of Thrones' Alum, 'Hamilton' Star|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=November 30, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=February 18, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.newsweek.com/aiden-gallagher-umbrella-academy-1332113 |title= 'The Umbrella Academy' Star Aidan Gallagher Says 'Comics Fans Are Going to Crazy' Over New Netflix Show |first=Janice |last=Williams |work=Newsweek |date=February 15, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGallagher is active on environmental issues, and has served as a youth advocate for a number of [[environmental organizations]], including [[Waterkeeper Alliance]], [[WildAid]] and [[Oceanic Preservation Society]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cleanseas.org/impact/aidan-gallagher-named-un-environment-goodwill-ambassador |title=Aidan Gallagher named UN Environment Goodwill Ambassador |work=Clean Seas }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/2018/06/05/world-environment-day-adrian-grenier-aidan-gallagher/ |title=Adrian Grenier and Aidan Gallagher Want You to Fight Plastic Pollution for World Environment Day |first=McKenna |last=Moore |date=June 5, 2018|work=Fortune }}</ref> He was named [[United Nations Environment Programme|UN Environment]] Goodwill Ambassador for North America in 2018 when he was 14, one of the youngest ever UN Goodwill Ambassador to be named.<ref name=Goodwill>{{cite web |url=https://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/press-release/aidan-gallagher-named-un-environment-goodwill-ambassador |title=Aidan Gallagher named UN Environment Goodwill Ambassador |date=3 June 2018 |work=UN Environment }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://etcanada.com/news/334724/aidan-gallagher-talks-new-netflix-show-the-umbrella-academy-and-world-environment-day/ |title=Aidan Gallagher Talks New Netflix Show 'The Umbrella Academy' And World Environment Day |first= Alyssa |last=Croezen|date= June 5, 2018 |work=ET Canada}}</ref> Gallagher moved to Toronto for the filming of Umbrella Academy, but mainly resides in LA. He befriended his neighbours, and was very social. His passions include educating others, singing, creating music, and reading. \n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2013 ||''You & Me''|| Young David || Short film\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2013 ||''[[Modern Family]]''|| Alec || Episode: \"The Wow Factor\"; uncredited<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm6200897/|title=Aidan Gallagher|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2013\n|''Jacked Up''\n|Evan\n|Pilot (unaired)<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n| 2014\u20132018 ||''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''|| Nicky || Main role\n|-\n| 2015 ||''Nickelodeon's Ho Ho Holiday Special''|| Himself || Television movie\n|-\n| 2017 ||''Nickelodeon's Sizzling Summer Camp Special''|| Beach Guy || Television movie; cameo\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present ||''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]''|| Number Five || Main role\n|}\n\n=== Music videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist(s)\n! Role\n|-\n| 2014 || \"We Make That Lemonade\" ||''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]'' cast\n|Nicky Harper\n|}\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2016\n| [[Young Artist Award]]\n| [[37th Young Artist Awards#Outstanding Young Ensemble Cast in a TV Series|Outstanding Young Ensemble Cast in a Television Series]]\n| ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''<br/>{{small|(shared with Casey Simpson, [[Lizzy Greene]] & [[Mace Coronel]])}} \n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://youngartistawards.org:80/2016-nominations-2/ |title=Nominations Young Artist Awards |website=[[Young Artist Awards]] |date=March 13, 2016 |accessdate=April 18, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424165415/http://youngartistawards.org/2016-nominations-2/ |archivedate=April 24, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[Kids' Choice Award]]\n|rowspan=2| [[Kids' Choice Award for Favorite Male TV Star|Favorite Male TV Star]]\n|rowspan=2| ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=kids2016 />\n|-\n| 2017\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=kids2017 />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|nm6200897}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gallagher, Aidan}}\n[[Category:2003 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Aidan Gallagher\n| image         = Aidan Gallagher - 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| caption       = Gallagher in 2018\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|2003|9|18}}\n| birth_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Actor, Singer\n| years_active  = 2013\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Aidan Gallagher''' (born September 18, 2003<ref>See: {{bulleted list \n|{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BKfRVYNBgfy/ |title=I'm official. ThirTEEN! |author=Gallagher, Aidan |publisher=aidanrgallagher |via=Instagram |date=September 18, 2016}}\n|{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BZKes23njEk/ |title=Thank you |author=Gallagher, Aidan |publisher=aidanrgallagher |via=Instagram |date=September 18, 2017 }} \n|{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bn3dRhDnBUX/ |title=15 \ud83c\udf82 |author=Gallagher, Aidan |publisher=aidanrgallagher |via=Instagram |date=September 18, 2018}} \n}}</ref>) is an American actor. His first major role was portraying one of the quadruplets, Nicky Harper, in the [[Nickelodeon]] television series ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/nickelodeon-greenlights-new-comedy-from-dan-schneider-two-other-live-action-series-698354/|title=Nickelodeon Greenlights New Comedy from Dan Schneider, Two Other Live-Action Series|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 13, 2014|access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, Gallagher began portraying Number Five in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/02/15/umbrella-academy-aidan-gallagher-number-five/ |title=Umbrella Academy actor explains how he nailed the timey-wimey weirdness of Number Five |first=Christian|last= Holub|date=February 15, 2019 |work=Entertainment Weekly }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGallagher first appeared in a minor role in a 2013 episode of ''[[Modern Family]]''. He was in the short film ''You & Me'' and was in the [[CBS]] television pilot ''Jacked Up'', which was not picked up and never aired.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/who-plays-number-5-in-the-umbrella-academy.html/|title=Who Plays Number 5 in 'The Umbrella Academy?'|last=Lezmi|first=Josh|last2=Articles|first2=More|date=2019-02-28|website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=March 04|first3=2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm6200897/bio|title=Aidan Gallagher - IMDb Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He then landed a major role in Nickelodeon's ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]'' as Nicky Harper,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/reviews/tv-review-nickelodeons-nicky-ricky-dicky-and-dawn-1201298288/ |title=TV Review: Nickelodeon's 'Nicky, Ricky, Dicky and Dawn' |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=September 12, 2014 }}</ref> for which he was nominated [[Kids' Choice Award for Favorite Male TV Star|Favorite Male TV Star]] in the [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]] in 2016 and 2017.<ref name=kids2016>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2016-kids-choice-award-nominees-867404/item/favorite-tv-show-2016-kids-867415 |title=Kids' Choice Awards: Adele, Justin Bieber, 'Star Wars' Among Nominees |date=  February 18, 2016|work=Hollywood Reporter }}</ref><ref name=kids2017>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/kids-choice-awards-complete-list-nominees-970757/item/2017-kids-choice-awards-favorite-tv-show-kids-show-970759 |title=Kids' Choice Awards: Justin Timberlake, Kevin Hart Top Nominations |date=February 2, 2017 |first= Lexy |last=Perez|work=Hollywood Reporter }}</ref> He was in the show for four seasons until it ended in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/school-of-rock-nicky-ricky-dicky-and-dawn-canceled-nickelodeon-1202616047/ |title='School of Rock,' 'Nicky, Ricky, Dicky and Dawn' Canceled at Nickelodeon |first= Joe |last= Otterson |work=Variety |date=November 15, 2018 }}</ref>  \n\nIn 2017, Gallagher was cast in the role of Number Five in ''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]'', which was released in February 2019 on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/umbrella-academy-series-netflix-cast-1202627134/|title='Umbrella Academy' Netflix Series Rounds Out Cast With 'Game of Thrones' Alum, 'Hamilton' Star|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=November 30, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=February 18, 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.newsweek.com/aiden-gallagher-umbrella-academy-1332113 |title= 'The Umbrella Academy' Star Aidan Gallagher Says 'Comics Fans Are Going to Crazy' Over New Netflix Show |first=Janice |last=Williams |work=Newsweek |date=February 15, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGallagher is active on environmental issues, and has served as a youth advocate for a number of [[environmental organizations]], including [[Waterkeeper Alliance]], [[WildAid]] and [[Oceanic Preservation Society]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cleanseas.org/impact/aidan-gallagher-named-un-environment-goodwill-ambassador |title=Aidan Gallagher named UN Environment Goodwill Ambassador |work=Clean Seas }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/2018/06/05/world-environment-day-adrian-grenier-aidan-gallagher/ |title=Adrian Grenier and Aidan Gallagher Want You to Fight Plastic Pollution for World Environment Day |first=McKenna |last=Moore |date=June 5, 2018|work=Fortune }}</ref> He was named [[United Nations Environment Programme|UN Environment]] Goodwill Ambassador for North America in 2018 when he was 14, one of the youngest ever UN Goodwill Ambassador to be named.<ref name=Goodwill>{{cite web |url=https://www.unenvironment.org/news-and-stories/press-release/aidan-gallagher-named-un-environment-goodwill-ambassador |title=Aidan Gallagher named UN Environment Goodwill Ambassador |date=3 June 2018 |work=UN Environment }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://etcanada.com/news/334724/aidan-gallagher-talks-new-netflix-show-the-umbrella-academy-and-world-environment-day/ |title=Aidan Gallagher Talks New Netflix Show 'The Umbrella Academy' And World Environment Day |first= Alyssa |last=Croezen|date= June 5, 2018 |work=ET Canada}}</ref> Gallagher moved to Toronto for the filming of Umbrella Academy, but mainly resides in LA. He befriended his neighbours, and was very social.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2013 ||''You & Me''|| Young David || Short film\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2013 ||''[[Modern Family]]''|| Alec || Episode: \"The Wow Factor\"; uncredited<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm6200897/|title=Aidan Gallagher|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|2013\n|''Jacked Up''\n|Evan\n|Pilot (unaired)<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n| 2014\u20132018 ||''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''|| Nicky || Main role\n|-\n| 2015 ||''Nickelodeon's Ho Ho Holiday Special''|| Himself || Television movie\n|-\n| 2017 ||''Nickelodeon's Sizzling Summer Camp Special''|| Beach Guy || Television movie; cameo\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present ||''[[The Umbrella Academy (TV series)|The Umbrella Academy]]''|| Number Five || Main role\n|}\n\n=== Music videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist(s)\n! Role\n|-\n| 2014 || \"We Make That Lemonade\" ||''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]'' cast\n|Nicky Harper\n|}\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2016\n| [[Young Artist Award]]\n| [[37th Young Artist Awards#Outstanding Young Ensemble Cast in a TV Series|Outstanding Young Ensemble Cast in a Television Series]]\n| ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''<br/>{{small|(shared with Casey Simpson, [[Lizzy Greene]] & [[Mace Coronel]])}} \n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://youngartistawards.org:80/2016-nominations-2/ |title=Nominations Young Artist Awards |website=[[Young Artist Awards]] |date=March 13, 2016 |accessdate=April 18, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424165415/http://youngartistawards.org/2016-nominations-2/ |archivedate=April 24, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[Kids' Choice Award]]\n|rowspan=2| [[Kids' Choice Award for Favorite Male TV Star|Favorite Male TV Star]]\n|rowspan=2| ''[[Nicky, Ricky, Dicky & Dawn]]''\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=kids2016 />\n|-\n| 2017\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=kids2017 />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|nm6200897}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gallagher, Aidan}}\n[[Category:2003 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n", "name_user": "Thereseseljak", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aidan_Gallagher"}
{"title_page": "Indeterminacy (music)", "text_new": "{{Use Harvard referencing|date=May 2019}}\n'''Indeterminacy''' is a composing approach in which some aspects of a musical work are left open to chance or to the interpreter's free choice. [[John Cage]], a pioneer of indeterminacy, defined it as \"the ability of a piece to be performed in substantially different ways\".\n\nThe earliest significant use of music indeterminacy features is found in many of the compositions of American composer [[Charles Ives]] in the early 20th century. [[Henry Cowell]] adopted Ives\u2019s ideas during the 1930s, in works allowing players to arrange the fragments of music in a number of different possible sequences. Beginning in the early 1950s, the term came to refer to the (mostly American) movement which grew up around Cage. This group included the other members of the [[New York School (art)#The composers|New York School]]. In Europe, following the introduction of the expression \"[[aleatory music]]\" by Meyer-Eppler, the French composer [[Pierre Boulez]] was largely responsible for popularizing the term.\n\n==Definition==\nDescribing indeterminacy, composer John Cage said: \"My intention is to let things be themselves\". Cage initially defined indeterminacy as \"the ability of a piece to be performed in substantially different ways\" {{harv|Pritchett|1993|loc=108}}. Bryan Simms thus conflates indeterminacy with what Cage called chance composition when he claims that \"Any part of a musical work is indeterminate if it is chosen by chance, or if its performance is not precisely specified. The former case is called 'indeterminacy of composition'; the latter is called 'indeterminacy of performance'\" {{harv|Simms|1986|loc=357}}.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest significant use of music indeterminacy features is found in many of the compositions of American composer [[Charles Ives]] in the early 20th century. [[Henry Cowell]] adopted Ives's ideas during the 1930s, in such works as the ''Mosaic Quartet'' (String Quartet No. 3, 1934), which allows the players to arrange the fragments of music in a number of different possible sequences. Cowell also used specially devised notations to introduce variability into the performance of a work, sometimes instructing the performers to improvise a short passage or play ''ad libitum.'' [[John Cage]] is regarded as a pioneer of indeterminacy in music. Beginning in the early 1950s, the term came to refer to the (mostly American) movement which grew up around Cage. This group included the other members of the so-called [[New York School (art)#The composers|New York School]]: [[Earle Brown]], [[Morton Feldman]] and [[Christian Wolff (composer)|Christian Wolff]]. Others working in this way included the [[Scratch Orchestra]] in the United Kingdom (1968 until the early 1970s) and the Japanese composer [[Toshi Ichiyanagi]] (born 1933). In Europe, following the introduction of the expression \"[[aleatory music]]\" by [[Werner Meyer-Eppler]], the French composer [[Pierre Boulez]] was largely responsible for popularizing the term {{harv|Boulez|1957}}.\n\nIn 1958 Cage gave two lectures in Europe, the first at Darmstadt, titled simply \"Indeterminacy\" {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=35\u201340}}, the second in Brussels called \"Indeterminacy: New Aspect of Form in Instrumental and Electronic Music\" (given again in an expanded form in 1959 at Teacher's College, Columbia). This second lecture consisted of a number of short stories (originally 30, expanded to ninety in the second version), each story read by Cage in exactly one minute; because of this time limit, the speed of Cage's delivery varied enormously {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=260}}. The second performance and a subsequent recording {{harv|Cage|1959}} contained music, also by Cage, played by [[David Tudor]] at the same time. Subsequently, Cage added still more stories, and published a selection of them, partly as an article, \"Indeterminacy\" {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=260\u201373}}, and partly as scattered interludes throughout his first collection of writings, ''Silence'' {{harv|Cage|1961}}.\n\nBetween 2007 and 2013, the Dutch artist [[Iebele Abel]] developed an electronic instrument called ''Real-time Indeterminate Synthetic Music Feedback'' (RT-ISMF). The instrument was designed for empirical research on subjective experiences induced by real-time synthesized music, based on the output of electronic random number generators. The basic idea of this approach was that indeterminate music might evoke unique and exceptional human experience {{harv|Abel|2013|loc=26, 117\u201319}}.\n\n==Classification==\nIndeterminate or chance music can be divided into three groups: (1) the use of random procedures to produce a determinate, fixed score, (2) mobile form, and (3) indeterminate notation, including graphic notation and texts. The first group includes scores in which the chance element is involved only in the process of composition, so that every parameter is fixed before their performance. In John Cage\u2019s ''[[Music of Changes]]'' (1951), the process of composition involved applying decisions made using the ''[[I Ching]]'', a Chinese classic text that is commonly used as a divination system. The ''I Ching'' was applied to large charts of sounds, durations, dynamics, tempo and densities. Cage himself, however, regarded ''Music of Changes'' as a determinate work, because it is completely fixed from one performance to another {{harv|Pritchett|1993|loc=108}}. [[Iannis Xenakis]] used probability theories to define some microscopic aspects of ''[[Pithoprakta]]'' (1955\u201356), that is the Greek for \"actions by means of probability\". This work contains four sections, characterized by textural and timbral attributes, such as glissandi and pizzicati. At the macroscopic level, the sections are designed and controlled by the composer, but the single components of sound are generated by mathematical theories {{harv|Joe and Song|2002|loc=268}}. See: [[stochastic music]].\n\nIn the second type of indeterminate music (the only type of indeterminate music according to Cage's definition), chance elements involve the performance. Notated events are provided by the composer, but their arrangement is left to the determination of the performer. According to Cage,  examples include [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s ''[[Art of Fugue]]'', Morton Feldman's ''Intersection 3'', Earle Brown's ''Four Systems'', and Christian Wolff's ''Duo for Pianists II'' {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=35\u201339}}. A form of limited indeterminacy was used by [[Witold Lutos\u0142awski]] (beginning with ''[[Jeux v\u00e9nitiens]]'' in 1960\u201361) {{harv|Rae|2001}}, where extensive passages of pitches and rhythms are fully specified, but the rhythmic coordination of parts within the ensemble is subject to an element of chance. Earle Brown\u2019s ''Twenty-Five Pages'', uses 25 unbound pages, and called for anywhere between one and 25 pianists. The score allowed the performer(s) to arrange the pages in whatever order they saw fit. Also, the pages were notated symmetrically and without clefs so that the top and bottom orientation is reversible.\n\n\"Open form\" is a term sometimes used for \"mobile\" or \"polyvalent\" musical forms, where the order of movements or sections is indeterminate or left up to the performer. [[Roman Haubenstock-Ramati]] composed a series of influential \"mobiles\" such as ''Interpolation'' (1958).\n\nHowever, \"open form\" in music is also used in the sense defined by the art historian Heinrich W\u00f6lfflin (1915) to mean a work which is fundamentally incomplete, represents an unfinished activity, or points outside of itself. In this sense, a \"mobile form\" can be either \"open\" or \"closed\". An example of a \"dynamic, closed\" mobile musical composition is [[Karlheinz Stockhausen]]'s ''[[Zyklus]]'' (1959) {{harv|Maconie|2005|loc=185}}. [[Terry Riley]]'s ''[[In C]]'' (1964) was composed of 53 short sequences; each member of the ensemble can repeat a given sequence as many times as desired before going on to the next, making the details of each performance of ''In C'' unique. However, because the overall course is fixed, it is a closed form.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nThe greatest degree of indeterminacy is reached by the third type of indeterminate music, in [[graphic notation (music)|graphic score]] pieces, in which the music is represented using symbols and illustrations suggesting how a work can be performed. [[Hans-Christoph Steiner]]'s score for ''Solitude'', created using Pure Data's data structures.This notation may be, like music on traditional staves, a time-pitch graph system. [[Earle Brown]]'s  ''December 1952'' consists purely of horizontal and vertical lines varying in width, spread out over the page; it is a landmark piece in the history of graphic notation of music. The role of the performer is to interpret the score visually and translate the graphical information to music. In Brown's notes on the work he even suggests that one consider this 2D space as 3D and imagine moving through it. [[Cornelius Cardew]]'s ''[[Treatise (music)|Treatise]]'' is a graphic musical score comprising 193 pages of lines, symbols, and various geometric or abstract shapes that generally eschew conventional musical notation. Although the score allows for absolute interpretive freedom (no one interpretation will sound like another), the work is not normally played spontaneously, as Cardew had previously suggested that performers devise in advance their own rules and methods for interpreting and performing the work. There are, however, infinite possibilities for the interpretation of ''Treatise'' that fall within the implications of the piece and general principles of experimental music performance in the late 1960s, including presentation as visual art and map-reading.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Discography==\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Cage|1959}}|reference=Cage, John. 1959. ''Indeterminacy: New Aspects of Form in Instrumental and Electronic Music''. Ninety Stories by John Cage, with Music. John Cage, reading; David Tudor, music (Cage, ''Solo for Piano'' from ''Concert for Piano and Orchestra'', with ''Fontana Mix''). Folkways FT 3704 (2 LPs). Reissued 1992 on Smithsonian/Folkways CD DF 40804/5 (2 CDs).}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Process music]]\n\n==References==\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Abel|2013}}|reference=Abel, Iebele. 2013. ''Manifestations of Mind in Matter''. Princeton: ICRL Press. {{ISBN|978-1936033072}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Boulez|1957}}|reference=Boulez, Pierre. 1957. \u201cAl\u00e9a\u201d. Nouvelle revue fran\u00e7aise, no. 59 (1 November): 839\u201357.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Cage|1961}}|reference=Cage, John. 1961. ''Silence: Lectures and Writings''. Middletown, Conn.: Wesleyan University Press.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Griffiths|2001}}|reference=Griffiths, Paul. 2001. \"Aleatory\". ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (musicologist)|John Tyrrell]]. London: Macmillan Publishers.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Joe  and Song|2002}}|reference=Joe, Jeongwon, and S. Hoon Song. 2002. \"Roland Barthes' \u2019Text\u2019 and Aleatoric Music: Is the Birth of the Reader the Birth of the Listener?\". ''Muzikologija'' 2:263\u201381.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Peyser|2008}}|reference=Peyser, Joan. 2008. ''To Boulez and Beyond'', revised edition. Lanham, Maryland: Scarecrow Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8108-5877-0}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Pritchett|1993}}|reference=Pritchett, James. 1993. ''The Music of John Cage''. Music in the 20th Century. Cambridge, New York, Melbourne: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-41621-3}} (cloth); {{ISBN|0-521-56544-8}} (pbk).}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Rae|2001}}|reference=Rae, Charles Bodman. 2001.  \"Lutos\u0142awski, Witold (Roman)\". ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (musicologist)|John Tyrrell]]. London: Macmillan Publishers.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Roig-Francol\u00ed|2008}}|reference=Roig-Francol\u00ed, Miguel A. 2008. ''Understanding Post-Tonal Music''. Boston: McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|0-07-293624-X}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Simms|1986}}|reference=Simms, Bryan R. 1986. ''Music of the Twentieth Century: Style and Structure''. New York: Schirmer Books; London: Collier Macmillan Publishers. {{ISBN|0-02-872580-8}}.}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Childs|1974}}|reference=Childs, Barney. 1974. \"Indeterminacy\". ''Dictionary of Twentieth-Century Music'', edited by John Vinton. London: Thames and Hudson. {{ISBN|0-500-01100-1}} American edition published under title ''Dictionary of Contemporary Music'' (New York: E. P. Dutton, 1974) {{ISBN|0-525-09125-4}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Nyman|1974}}|reference=Nyman, Michael. 1974. ''Experimental Music: Cage and Beyond''. London: Studio Vista; New York: Schirmer Books. {{ISBN|0-02-871200-5}} Second edition 1999, Cambridge and New York: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-65297-9}} (cloth) {{ISBN|0-521-65383-5}} (pbk).}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Sutherland|1994}}|reference=Sutherland, Roger. 1994. ''New Perspectives in Music''. London: Sun Tavern Fields. {{ISBN|0-9517012-6-6}}.}}\n\n[[Category:Experimental music]]\n[[Category:Musical composition]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Harvard referencing|date=May 2019}}\n'''Indeterminacy''' is a composing approach in which some aspects of a musical work are left open to chance or to the interpreter's free choice. [[John Cage]], a pioneer of indeterminacy, defined it as \"the ability of a piece to be performed in substantially different ways\".\n\nThe earliest significant use of music indeterminacy features is found in many of the compositions of American composer [[Charles Ives]] in the early 20th century. [[Henry Cowell]] adopted Ives\u2019s ideas during the 1930s, in works allowing players to arrange the fragments of music in a number of different possible sequences. Beginning in the early 1950s, the term came to refer to the (mostly American) movement which grew up around Cage. This group included the other members of the [[New York School (art)#The composers|New York School]]. In Europe, following the introduction of the expression \"[[aleatory music]]\" by Meyer-Eppler, the French composer [[Pierre Boulez]] was largely responsible for popularizing the term.\n\n==Definition==\nDescribing indeterminacy, composer John Cage said: \"My intention is to let things be themselves\". Cage initially defined indeterminacy as \"the ability of a piece to be performed in substantially different ways\" {{harv|Pritchett|1993|loc=108}}. Bryan Simms thus conflates indeterminacy with what Cage called chance composition when he claims that \"Any part of a musical work is indeterminate if it is chosen by chance, or if its performance is not precisely specified. The former case is called 'indeterminacy of composition'; the latter is called 'indeterminacy of performance'\" {{harv|Simms|1986|loc=357}}.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest significant use of music indeterminacy features is found in many of the compositions of American composer [[Charles Ives]] in the early 20th century. [[Henry Cowell]] adopted Ives's ideas during the 1930s, in such works as the ''Mosaic Quartet'' (String Quartet No. 3, 1934), which allows the players to arrange the fragments of music in a number of different possible sequences. Cowell also used specially devised notations to introduce variability into the performance of a work, sometimes instructing the performers to improvise a short passage or play ''ad libitum.'' [[John Cage]] is regarded as a pioneer of indeterminacy in music. Beginning in the early 1950s, the term came to refer to the (mostly American) movement which grew up around Cage. This group included the other members of the so-called [[New York School (art)#The composers|New York School]]: [[Earle Brown]], [[Morton Feldman]] and [[Christian Wolff (composer)|Christian Wolff]]. Others working in this way included the [[Scratch Orchestra]] in the United Kingdom (1968 until the early 1970s) and the Japanese composer [[Toshi Ichiyanagi]] (born 1933). In Europe, following the introduction of the expression \"[[aleatory music]]\" by [[Werner Meyer-Eppler]], the French composer [[Pierre Boulez]] was largely responsible for popularizing the term {{harv|Boulez|1957}}.\n\nIn 1958 Cage gave two lectures in Europe, the first at Darmstadt, titled simply \"Indeterminacy\" {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=35\u201340}}, the second in Brussels called \"Indeterminacy: New Aspect of Form in Instrumental and Electronic Music\" (given again in an expanded form in 1959 at Teacher's College, Columbia). This second lecture consisted of a number of short stories (originally 30, expanded to ninety in the second version), each story read by Cage in exactly one minute; because of this time limit, the speed of Cage's delivery varied enormously {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=260}}. The second performance and a subsequent recording {{harv|Cage|1959}} contained music, also by Cage, played by [[David Tudor]] at the same time. Subsequently, Cage added still more stories, and published a selection of them, partly as an article, \"Indeterminacy\" {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=260\u201373}}, and partly as scattered interludes throughout his first collection of writings, ''Silence'' {{harv|Cage|1961}}.\n\nBetween 2007 and 2013, the Dutch artist [[Iebele Abel]] developed an electronic instrument called ''Real-time Indeterminate Synthetic Music Feedback'' (RT-ISMF). The instrument was designed for empirical research on subjective experiences induced by real-time synthesized music, based on the output of electronic random number generators. The basic idea of this approach was that indeterminate music might evoke unique and exceptional human experience {{harv|Abel|2013|loc=26, 117\u201319}}.\n\n==Classification==\nIndeterminate or chance music can be divided into three groups: (1) the use of random procedures to produce a determinate, fixed score, (2) mobile form, and (3) indeterminate notation, including graphic notation and texts. The first group includes scores in which the chance element is involved only in the process of composition, so that every parameter is fixed before their performance. In John Cage\u2019s ''[[Music of Changes]]'' (1951), the process of composition involved applying decisions made using the ''[[I Ching]]'', a Chinese classic text that is commonly used as a divination system. The ''I Ching'' was applied to large charts of sounds, durations, dynamics, tempo and densities. Cage himself, however, regarded ''Music of Changes'' as a determinate work, because it is completely fixed from one performance to another {{harv|Pritchett|1993|loc=108}}. [[Iannis Xenakis]] used probability theories to define some microscopic aspects of ''[[Pithoprakta]]'' (1955\u201356), that is the Greek for \"actions by means of probability\". This work contains four sections, characterized by textural and timbral attributes, such as glissandi and pizzicati. At the macroscopic level, the sections are designed and controlled by the composer, but the single components of sound are generated by mathematical theories {{harv|Joe and Song|2002|loc=268}}. See: [[stochastic music]].\n\nIn the second type of indeterminate music (the only type of indeterminate music according to Cage's definition), chance elements involve the performance. Notated events are provided by the composer, but their arrangement is left to the determination of the performer. According to Cage,  examples include [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]'s ''[[Art of Fugue]]'', Morton Feldman's ''Intersection 3'', Earle Brown's ''Four Systems'', and Christian Wolff's ''Duo for Pianists II'' {{harv|Cage|1961|loc=35\u201339}}. A form of limited indeterminacy was used by [[Witold Lutos\u0142awski]] (beginning with ''[[Jeux v\u00e9nitiens]]'' in 1960\u201361) {{harv|Rae|2001}}, where extensive passages of pitches and rhythms are fully specified, but the rhythmic coordination of parts within the ensemble is subject to an element of chance. Earle Brown\u2019s ''Twenty-Five Pages'', uses 25 unbound pages, and called for anywhere between one and 25 pianists. The score allowed the performer(s) to arrange the pages in whatever order they saw fit. Also, the pages were notated symmetrically and without clefs so that the top and bottom orientation is reversible.\n\n\"Open form\" is a term sometimes used for \"mobile\" or \"polyvalent\" musical forms, where the order of movements or sections is indeterminate or left up to the performer. [[Roman Haubenstock-Ramati]] composed a series of influential \"mobiles\" such as ''Interpolation'' (1958).\n\nHowever, \"open form\" in music is also used in the sense defined by the art historian Heinrich W\u00f6lfflin (1915) to mean a work which is fundamentally incomplete, represents an unfinished activity, or points outside of itself. In this sense, a \"mobile form\" can be either \"open\" or \"closed\". An example of a \"dynamic, closed\" mobile musical composition is [[Karlheinz Stockhausen]]'s ''[[Zyklus]]'' (1959) {{harv|Maconie|2005|loc=185}}. [[Terry Riley]]'s ''[[In C]]'' (1964) was composed of 53 short sequences; each member of the ensemble can repeat a given sequence as many times as desired before going on to the next, making the details of each performance of ''In C'' unique. However, because the overall course is fixed, it is a closed form.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nThe greatest degree of indeterminacy is reached by the third type of indeterminate music, in [[graphic notation (music)|graphic score]] pieces, in which the music is represented using symbols and illustrations suggesting how a work can be performed. [[Hans-Christoph Steiner]]'s score for ''Solitude'', created using Pure Data's data structures.This notation may be, like music on traditional staves, a time-pitch graph system. [[Earle Brown]]'s  ''December 1952'' consists purely of horizontal and vertical lines varying in width, spread out over the page; it is a landmark piece in the history of graphic notation of music. The role of the performer is to interpret the score visually and translate the graphical information to music. In Brown's notes on the work he even suggests that one consider this 2D space as 3D and imagine moving through it. [[Cornelius Cardew]]'s ''[[Treatise (music)|Treatise]]'' is a graphic musical score comprising 193 pages of lines, symbols, and various geometric or abstract shapes that generally eschew conventional musical notation. Although the score allows for absolute interpretive freedom (no one interpretation will sound like another), the work is not normally played spontaneously, as Cardew had previously suggested that performers devise in advance their own rules and methods for interpreting and performing the work. There are, however, infinite possibilities for the interpretation of ''Treatise'' that fall within the implications of the piece and general principles of experimental music performance in the late 1960s, including presentation as visual art and map-reading.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Discography==\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Cage|1959}}|reference=Cage, John. 1959. ''Indeterminacy: New Aspects of Form in Instrumental and Electronic Music''. Ninety Stories by John Cage, with Music. John Cage, reading; David Tudor, music (Cage, ''Solo for Piano'' from ''Concert for Piano and Orchestra'', with ''Fontana Mix''). Folkways FT 3704 (2 LPs). Reissued 1992 on Smithsonian/Folkways CD DF 40804/5 (2 CDs).}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Process music]]\n\n==References==\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Abel|2013}}|reference=Abel, Iebele. 2013. ''Manifestations of Mind in Matter''. Princeton: ICRL Press. {{ISBN|978-1936033072}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Boulez|1957}}|reference=Boulez, Pierre. 1957. \u201cAl\u00e9a\u201d. Nouvelle revue fran\u00e7aise, no. 59 (1 November): 839\u201357.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Cage|1961}}|reference=Cage, John. 1961. ''Silence: Lectures and Writings''. Middletown, Conn.: Wesleyan University Press.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Griffiths|2001}}|reference=Griffiths, Paul. 2001. \"Aleatory\". ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (musicologist)|John Tyrrell]]. London: Macmillan Publishers.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Joe  and Song|2002}}|reference=Joe, Jeongwon, and S. Hoon Song. 2002. \"Roland Barthes' \u2019Text\u2019 and Aleatoric Music: Is the Birth of the Reader the Birth of the Listener?\". ''Muzikologija'' 2:263\u201381.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Peyser|2008}}|reference=Peyser, Joan. 2008. ''To Boulez and Beyond'', revised edition. Lanham, Maryland: Scarecrow Press. {{ISBN|978\u20130\u20138108-5877-0}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Pritchett|1993}}|reference=Pritchett, James. 1993. ''The Music of John Cage''. Music in the 20th Century. Cambridge, New York, Melbourne: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-41621-3}} (cloth); {{ISBN|0-521-56544-8}} (pbk).}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Rae|2001}}|reference=Rae, Charles Bodman. 2001.  \"Lutos\u0142awski, Witold (Roman)\". ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (musicologist)|John Tyrrell]]. London: Macmillan Publishers.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Roig-Francol\u00ed|2008}}|reference=Roig-Francol\u00ed, Miguel A. 2008. ''Understanding Post-Tonal Music''. Boston: McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|0-07-293624-X}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Simms|1986}}|reference=Simms, Bryan R. 1986. ''Music of the Twentieth Century: Style and Structure''. New York: Schirmer Books; London: Collier Macmillan Publishers. {{ISBN|0-02-872580-8}}.}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Childs|1974}}|reference=Childs, Barney. 1974. \"Indeterminacy\". ''Dictionary of Twentieth-Century Music'', edited by John Vinton. London: Thames and Hudson. {{ISBN|0-500-01100-1}} American edition published under title ''Dictionary of Contemporary Music'' (New York: E. P. Dutton, 1974) {{ISBN|0-525-09125-4}}.}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Nyman|1974}}|reference=Nyman, Michael. 1974. ''Experimental Music: Cage and Beyond''. London: Studio Vista; New York: Schirmer Books. {{ISBN|0-02-871200-5}} Second edition 1999, Cambridge and New York: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-65297-9}} (cloth) {{ISBN|0-521-65383-5}} (pbk).}}\n*{{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Sutherland|1994}}|reference=Sutherland, Roger. 1994. ''New Perspectives in Music''. London: Sun Tavern Fields. {{ISBN|0-9517012-6-6}}.}}\n\n[[Category:Experimental music]]\n[[Category:Musical composition]]\n", "name_user": "Jerome Kohl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indeterminacy_(music)"}
{"title_page": "Closing time effect", "text_new": "\"'''Closing time effect'''\" refers to the [[phenomenon]] that people's [[perception]] of other people's [[attractiveness]] increases as it gets later into the night. This observation was first coined by [[Mickey Gilley]] in his song, \"[[Don't the Girls All Get Prettier at Closing Time]]\" in [[1975]]. Subsequently, it caught the attention of [[social psychologist]]s who used scientific testing to gather evidence in support of the idea.\n\n==The first experiment==\n[[James W. Pennebaker]] et al. (1979) conducted the first [[experiment]] testing this [[observation]]. Using 52 males and 51 females as subjects at three [[bar]]s near a [[college campus]], experimenters asked individuals the following question: \"On a scale from 1 to 10, where 1 indicates 'not attractive', 5 indicates 'average', and 10 indicates 'extremely [[attractive]],' how would you rate the opposite-sex individuals here tonight.\" The experimenters took this survey at 9:00 pm, 10:30 pm and at midnight. Results showed that individuals' perception of people's [[attractiveness]] in the bar increased the later it got.\n\n==Theory==\nThe freedom of potentially going home with someone in the bar is threatened as the night comes closer to ending, according to the [[reactance (psychology)|reactance theory]] ([https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4675534/ Brehm, 1966]). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247745267_Don't_the_Girls'_Get_Prettier_at_Closing_Time_A_Country_and_Western_Application_to_Psychology Pennebaker et al. (1979)] also suggested [[dissonance theory]] as an explanation, proposing that as the night progresses, individuals intention to leave with someone becomes stronger. However, leaving the bar with someone who they may find unattractive causes [[Cognitive dissonance|dissonance]], increasing the perceived attractiveness of the potential mate.\n\n==Other studies==\nFollowing the first [[Research|study]] performed by [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247745267_Don't_the_Girls'_Get_Prettier_at_Closing_Time_A_Country_and_Western_Application_to_Psychology Pennebaker et al. in 1979], [https://www.academia.edu/18774441/They_do_get_prettier_at_closing_time_A_repeated_measures_study_of_the_closing-time_effect_and_alcohol Nida and Koon (1983)] found evidence of the closing time effect in a [[country and western]] bar but did not find it in a campus bar. [https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1990-28158-001 Gladue and Delaney (1990)] found that individuals of the opposite gender became more attractive as a factor of time, but that photos of the opposite gender did not. They found that male participants rated the most attractive photos higher but ratings of the least attractive photos also decreased. [[Females]] showed no changes over time in their photo ratings of males. [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1207/s15324834basp1804_2 Madey, Simo, Dillworth, and Kemper (1996)] found the effect in a nightclub near a university, but only for participants not in a [[Romance (love)|relationship]]. The authors argued that only participants not in a relationship should experience a threat to their choice of companion. [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0146167284103017 Sprecher et al. (1984)] did not find a closing-time effect.\n\n==The effect of alcohol==\nJohnco, Wheeler and Taylor (2010) measured the attractiveness of participants over a night while also controlling for the [[beer goggles|effect of alcohol consumption]] by measuring their [[blood alcohol content]] with a breathalyzer each time that they measured individuals' perceptions of physical attractiveness. They used BAC as a time varying [[covariate]] in a repeated measures design, with 87 participants at a beachside pub in [[Sydney]], Australia on four consecutive Saturday nights, between 9 pm and 12 am. They found that both perceptions of attractiveness as well as BAC increased as a factor of time. They concluded that BAC explained a significant portion of the increase in opposite-sex attractiveness but that a substantial effect remains after adjusting for BAC.\n\n==Other possible explanations==\nOne other possible explanation about the cause of this perception of higher attractiveness is \"mere familiarity or exposure\" ([https://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Fh0025848 Zajonc, 1968]). Previously seen stimuli may be perceived more positively than new stimuli. Another explanation comes from the commodity theory (Brock, 1968). According to [[commodity]] theory, as people find mates in the bar and leave with them, there is a scarcity of individuals left in the bar. This scarcity increases the desirability and perceived attractiveness of those left in the bar.\n\n==References==\n# [https://www.elsevier.com/books/psychological-reactance/brehm/978-0-12-129840-1 Brehm, J. W. (1966). A theory of psychological reactance. New York: Academic.]\n# Gilley, M. (1975). Don't all the girls get prettier at closing time. In The Best of Mickey Gilley (Vol. 2). Columbia Records. Written by Baker Knight, Singleton Music Company. New York: Broadcast Music, Inc.\n# [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12747502 Halberstadt, J., Rhodes, G., & Catty, S. R. (2003). Subjective and objective familiarity as explanations for the attraction to average faces. In F. Columbus (Ed.), Advances in psychology research (pp.&nbsp;91\u2013106). New York: Nova Science Publishers.]\n# [https://www.academia.edu/18774441/They_do_get_prettier_at_closing_time_A_repeated_measures_study_of_the_closing-time_effect_and_alcohol Nida, S. A., & Koon, J. (1983). They get better looking at closing time around here, too. Psychological Reports, 52(2), 657\u2013658.]\n# [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247745267_Don't_the_Girls'_Get_Prettier_at_Closing_Time_A_Country_and_Western_Application_to_Psychology Pennebaker, J. W., Dyer, M. A., Caulkins, R. S., Litowitz, D. L., Ackreman, P. L., Anderson, D. B., et al. (1979). Don't the girls get prettier at closing time: A country and western application to psychology. Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin, 5(1), 122\u2013125.]\n# [https://research-repository.uwa.edu.au/en/publications/subjective-and-objective-familiarity-as-explanations-for-the-attr The attractiveness of average faces is not a generalized mere exposure effect. Social Cognition, 23, 205\u2013217.]\n# [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233134890_They_do_get_prettier_at_closing_time_A_repeated_measures_study_of_the_closing-time_effect_and_alcohol Johnco, C., Wheeler, L,.& Taylor.A., (2010). They do get prettier at closing time: A repeated measures study of the closing-time effect and alcohol. Social Influence, 5:4, 261-271.]\n# [https://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Fh0025848 Zajonc, R. B. (1968). Attitudinal effects of mere exposure. Journal of personality and social psychology, 9(2p2), 1.]\n# Brock, T. C. (1968). Implications of commodity theory for value change. In Psychological foundations of attitudes (pp. 243-275). Academic Press.\n[[Category:Interpersonal attraction]]\n[[Category:Popular culture]]\n[[Category:Psychology]]\n", "text_old": "\"'''Closing time effect'''\" refers to the [[phenomenon]] that people's [[perception]] of other people's [[attractiveness]] increases as it gets later into the night. This observation was first coined by [[Mickey Gilley]] in his song, \"[[Don't the Girls All Get Prettier at Closing Time]]\" in [[1975]]. Subsequently, it caught the attention of [[social psychologist]]s who used scientific testing to gather evidence in support of the idea.\n\n==The first experiment==\n[[James W. Pennebaker]] et al. (1979) conducted the first [[experiment]] testing this [[observation]]. Using 52 males and 51 females as subjects at three [[bar]]s near a [[college campus]], experimenters asked individuals the following question: \"On a scale from 1 to 10, where 1 indicates 'not attractive', 5 indicates 'average', and 10 indicates 'extremely [[attractive]],' how would you rate the opposite-sex individuals here tonight.\" The experimenters took this survey at 9:00 pm, 10:30 pm and at midnight. Results showed that individuals' perception of people's [[attractiveness]] in the bar increased the later it got.\n\n==Theory==\nThe freedom of potentially going home with someone in the bar is threatened as the night comes closer to ending, according to the [[reactance (psychology)|reactance theory]] ([https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4675534/ Brehm, 1966]). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247745267_Don't_the_Girls'_Get_Prettier_at_Closing_Time_A_Country_and_Western_Application_to_Psychology Pennebaker et al. (1979)] also suggested [[dissonance theory]] as an explanation, proposing that as the night progresses, individuals intention to leave with someone becomes stronger. However, leaving the bar with someone who they may find unattractive causes [[Cognitive dissonance|dissonance]], increasing the perceived attractiveness of the potential mate.\n\n==Other studies==\nFollowing the first [[Research|study]] performed by [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247745267_Don't_the_Girls'_Get_Prettier_at_Closing_Time_A_Country_and_Western_Application_to_Psychology Pennebaker et al. in 1979], [https://www.academia.edu/18774441/They_do_get_prettier_at_closing_time_A_repeated_measures_study_of_the_closing-time_effect_and_alcohol Nida and Koon (1983)] found evidence of the closing time effect in a [[country]] and western bar but did not find it in a campus bar. [https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1990-28158-001 Gladue and Delaney (1990)] found that individuals of the opposite gender became more attractive as a factor of time, but that photos of the opposite gender did not. They found that male participants rated the most attractive photos higher but ratings of the least attractive photos also decreased. [[Females]] showed no changes over time in their photo ratings of males. [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1207/s15324834basp1804_2 Madey, Simo, Dillworth, and Kemper (1996)] found the effect in a nightclub near a university, but only for participants not in a [[Romance (love)|relationship]]. The authors argued that only participants not in a relationship should experience a threat to their choice of companion. [https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0146167284103017 Sprecher et al. (1984)] did not find a closing-time effect.\n\n==The effect of alcohol==\nJohnco, Wheeler and Taylor (2010) measured the attractiveness of participants over a night while also controlling for the [[beer goggles|effect of alcohol consumption]] by measuring their [[blood alcohol content]] with a breathalyzer each time that they measured individuals' perceptions of physical attractiveness. They used BAC as a time varying [[covariate]] in a repeated measures design, with 87 participants at a beachside pub in [[Sydney]], Australia on four consecutive Saturday nights, between 9 pm and 12 am. They found that both perceptions of attractiveness as well as BAC increased as a factor of time. They concluded that BAC explained a significant portion of the increase in opposite-sex attractiveness but that a substantial effect remains after adjusting for BAC.\n\n==Other possible explanations==\nOne other possible explanation about the cause of this perception of higher attractiveness is \"mere familiarity or exposure\" ([https://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Fh0025848 Zajonc, 1968]). Previously seen stimuli may be perceived more positively than new stimuli. Another explanation comes from the commodity theory (Brock, 1968). According to [[commodity]] theory, as people find mates in the bar and leave with them, there is a scarcity of individuals left in the bar. This scarcity increases the desirability and perceived attractiveness of those left in the bar.\n\n==References==\n# [https://www.elsevier.com/books/psychological-reactance/brehm/978-0-12-129840-1 Brehm, J. W. (1966). A theory of psychological reactance. New York: Academic.]\n# Gilley, M. (1975). Don't all the girls get prettier at closing time. In The Best of Mickey Gilley (Vol. 2). Columbia Records. Written by Baker Knight, Singleton Music Company. New York: Broadcast Music, Inc.\n# [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12747502 Halberstadt, J., Rhodes, G., & Catty, S. R. (2003). Subjective and objective familiarity as explanations for the attraction to average faces. In F. Columbus (Ed.), Advances in psychology research (pp.&nbsp;91\u2013106). New York: Nova Science Publishers.]\n# [https://www.academia.edu/18774441/They_do_get_prettier_at_closing_time_A_repeated_measures_study_of_the_closing-time_effect_and_alcohol Nida, S. A., & Koon, J. (1983). They get better looking at closing time around here, too. Psychological Reports, 52(2), 657\u2013658.]\n# [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/247745267_Don't_the_Girls'_Get_Prettier_at_Closing_Time_A_Country_and_Western_Application_to_Psychology Pennebaker, J. W., Dyer, M. A., Caulkins, R. S., Litowitz, D. L., Ackreman, P. L., Anderson, D. B., et al. (1979). Don't the girls get prettier at closing time: A country and western application to psychology. Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin, 5(1), 122\u2013125.]\n# [https://research-repository.uwa.edu.au/en/publications/subjective-and-objective-familiarity-as-explanations-for-the-attr The attractiveness of average faces is not a generalized mere exposure effect. Social Cognition, 23, 205\u2013217.]\n# [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233134890_They_do_get_prettier_at_closing_time_A_repeated_measures_study_of_the_closing-time_effect_and_alcohol Johnco, C., Wheeler, L,.& Taylor.A., (2010). They do get prettier at closing time: A repeated measures study of the closing-time effect and alcohol. Social Influence, 5:4, 261-271.]\n# [https://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Fh0025848 Zajonc, R. B. (1968). Attitudinal effects of mere exposure. Journal of personality and social psychology, 9(2p2), 1.]\n# Brock, T. C. (1968). Implications of commodity theory for value change. In Psychological foundations of attitudes (pp. 243-275). Academic Press.\n[[Category:Interpersonal attraction]]\n[[Category:Popular culture]]\n[[Category:Psychology]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closing_time_effect"}
{"title_page": "Convoy HX 65", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Convoy HX.65\n|partof=[[World War II]]\n|date=24\u201327 August 1940\n|place=[[North Atlantic]]\n|combatant1=[[File:War Ensign of Germany 1938-1945.svg|25px]] [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]\n|combatant2={{navy|Canada|1921}}<br>[[File:Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg|25px]] [[United Kingdom]]\n|commander1=[[Admiral]] [[Karl D\u00f6nitz]]\n|commander2=Vice-Admiral B G Washington CMG DSO (Commodore)<br>Rear-Admiral E W Leir DSO (Vice-Commodore)\n|strength1=5 [[U-Boat|U-boats]]\n|strength2=51 merchant ships<br>7 escorts\n|casualties1=1 U-boat damaged\n|casualties2=8 ships sunk<br>3 damaged\n|campaignbox={{campaignbox Atlantic Campaign}}\n}}\n'''Convoy HX 65''' was a [[North Atlantic]] [[convoy]] of the [[HX convoys|HX series]] which ran during the [[battle of the Atlantic]] in [[World War II]]. It was the 65th of the numbered series of merchant convoy] run by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] from [[Halifax Harbour|Halifax]] to [[Liverpool]]. The convoy was attacked by [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[U-boat]]s and aircraft, losing eight of its 51 ships sunk and a further three damaged. One U-boat was damaged.\n\n==Background==\nHX 65 formed of three sections sailing from the Americas, and was to divide into two sections for the landfall in the [[United Kingdom]]. \nThe main body, of 13 ships,  departed Halifax on 12 August 1940;<ref>Hague, p.126</ref> with ships gathered from the US eastern seaboard; it was led by [[convoy commodore]] [[Vice Admiral|V.Adm.]] BG Washington in the steamship ''Harpalyce''. It was accompanied by its ocean escort, the [[Armed Merchant Cruiser]] ''Voltaire'', and a local escort of two [[Royal Canadian Navy|RCN]] warships. \nIt was joined on 14 August by 16 ships from [[Sydney, Nova Scotia|Sydney]], on [[Cape Breton Island]], also with a local escort. These had gathered from ports on the [[Saint Lawrence River|St Lawrence]] and the [[Great Lakes]].<ref>Hague, Arnold; HX 65 at convoyweb.org.uk</ref>\nOn 16 August the convoy was joined by BHX 65, 22 ships from the [[Caribbean]] and [[South America]], that had gathered at [[Bermuda]], departing there on 11 August escorted by the AMC ''Montclare''.<ref>Hague, Arnold; BHX 65 at convoyweb.org.uk</ref> \n\nRanged against HX 65 were U-boats of the [[Kriegsmarine|German Navy's]] [[1st U-boat Flotilla|1st]], [[2nd U-boat Flotilla|2nd]] and [[7th U-boat Flotilla|7th]] U-boat Flotillas, operating from [[Kiel]] and [[Wilhelmshaven]].\n\n==Action==\nOn 22 August HX 65\u2019s Western Approaches escort began to arrive; the destroyer {{HMCS|Skeena|D59|2}} and the corvette {{HMS|Godetia|K72|2}} left the outbound OA 201, arriving later that day. On 24 August the destroyer {{HMS|Westcott|D47|2}} and the corvette {{HMS|Gladiolus|K34|2}} arrived from OB 201.<ref>Hague lists ''Gladiolus'' as escort for OB 201 with ''Westcott'', but not joining HX 65. Uboat.net has ''Gladiolus'' joining HX 65 with ''Westcott'' on 24th, but from OA 201.</ref>  \n\nOn the morning of 24 August  tanker ''La Brea'' (one of two ships that had dropped out of HX 65 5 days earlier) was sighted by {{GS|U-48|1939|2}} in the North West Approaches WNW of [[Rockall]]. She was attacked and sunk, leaving two boats of survivors in bad weather and rough seas. They made landfall in the [[Hebrides]] over the next two days.<ref>Blair p181</ref><ref>[https://www.uboat.net/ops/convoys/convoys.php?convoy=HX-65 HX 65] at uboat.net; retrieved 19 April 2020</ref> \n\nOn the evening of 24 August the convoy divided, one section (referred to in some sources as HX 65A) of 20 ships bound for [[Methil]] on Scotland\u2019s east coast via [[Cape Wrath]] and the north of Scotland, and a second section (HX 65 B) of 22 ships bound for Liverpool.\n\nThe Methil section, led by ''Harpalyce'' and  escorted by ''Skeena'' and ''Godetia'' was found by ''U-48'', which  attacked during the night of 24/25 August, sinking 2 ships, ''Empire Merlin'' and ''Athelcrest''. She was counter attacked by ''Godetia'' but escaped without damage.\nLater, on the morning of 25 August the convoy was sighted twice more, by {{GS|U-28|1936|2}} and {{GS|U-32|1937|2}}, but the convoy had been joined by a [[Short Sunderland|Sunderland]] from [[Coastal Command]], and both submerged on sighting the aircraft. ''U-32'' made a perfunctory attack, which failed.\nThat evening the convoy was found again, by {{GS|U-124|1940|2}}, and attacked just before midnight. ''U-124'' fired four torpedoes and claimed four ships sunk; the actual success was two ships sunk (''Harpalyce'' and ''Fircrest'') and another (''[[SS Stakesby (1930)|Stakesby]]'') damaged. ''Harpalyce'' and ''Fircrest'' went down quickly with heavy loss of life. ''Stakesby'' was abandoned, but was later salvaged by the tug ''[[HMT Thames (1938)|Thames]]'' and repaired. ''U-124'' was counterattacked by ''Godetia'' and damaged when she ran onto a rock. After the corvette had left, ''U-124'' was unable to continue convoy operations relegated to weather reporting.<ref>Blair p181-182</ref> \nLater that day the convoy was reinforced by {{HMS|Jaguar|F34|2}} and {{HMS|Javelin|F61|2}}, two destroyers from [[Scapa Flow]].<ref>[https://www.uboat.net/ops/convoys/convoys.php?convoy=HX-65A  HX 65A] at uboat.net; retrieved 19 April 2020</ref>\nOn the evening of 26 August  the convoy came under air attack near [[Kinnaird Head]] by ''Luftwaffe'' aircraft from occupied Norway; eight [[Junkers Ju 88|Ju 88]]s of KG 30 based at [[Aalborg]]. four ships were hit; one was sunk and three damaged. ''Nellie'' and ''City of Hankow'' made port safely, but ''Cape York'' sank under tow on the following day. Later on the night of 26/27 August a second air attack by four [[Heinkel He 115|He 115]] torpedo bombers of KuFlGr 506, based in  [[Stavanger]], hit ''Remuera'', which sank. The remaining 16 ships arrived at safely at  Methil on 27th.<ref>Hague, Arnold; HX 65 at convoyweb.org.uk</ref>\n\nMeanwhile on 25 August the Liverpool section, led by V.Adm. Leir in ''Manchester Merchant'' and escorted by ''Westcott'', was found by {{GS|U-57|1938|2}} which gave chase. Several tankers had fallen out of the convoy, to be chivvied by the escort, and one of these, ''Pecten'', was torpedoed by ''U-57''. The escort counter-attacked, but ''U-57'' escaped. This section was also reinforced on 26 August, by the sloop {{HMS|Lowestoft|L59|2}}. No further attacks developed and the 21 ships arrived without further incident at Liverpool on 27 August.<ref>Blair p184</ref><ref>[https://www.uboat.net/ops/convoys/convoys.php?convoy=HX-65B HX 65B] at uboat.net; retrieved 19 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Forces involved==\n===Allied forces===\n====Merchant ships====\nConvoy information is from Arnold Hague's Convoyweb<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.convoyweb.org.uk/HX/index.html|title=Convoy HX.65|publisher=Arnold Hague Convoy Database|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Merchant ships\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150px\"  |Name\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150px\"  |Flag\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"30px\"   |Tonnage [[gross register tons|(GRT)]]\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100px\"  |Section\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"300px\"  |Notes\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Agapenor'' (1914)\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|align=\"right\"|7,391\n|align=\"left\"|HX\n|align=\"left\"|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Alfred Olsen'' (1934)\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry|Norway}}\n|align=\"right\"|8,817\n|align=\"left\"|BHX 65\n|align=\"left\"|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Anna Mazaraki'' (1913)\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry|Greece}}\n|align=\"right\"|5,411\n|align=\"left\"|SHX\n|align=\"left\"|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Aspasia Nomikos'' (1938)\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry|Greece}}\n|align=\"right\"|4,855\n|align=\"left\"|SHX \n|align=\"left\"|en route to Dublin\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Athelcrest'' (1940)\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|align=\"right\"|6,825\n|align=\"left